In a Nov. 4, 2014 file photo, "I VOTED" stickers lie on a table in the Norton Shores Library in Norton Shores, Mich. Michigan voters who with a single mark can vote Democratic or Republican for every partisan office on the ballot may no longer have the option in 2016. Republicans who control the Legislature want to make Michigan the latest state to eliminate straight-ticket, or straight-party, voting. It is still used in 10 states but has been abolished by nine others in the last 20 years, including nearby Wisconsin and Illinois. (MLive.com File Photo) (AP)
